I got a start on editing a tiny portion of the video I shot while I was visiting @jefflefkowitz last month.
-
The first series of videos covers the Six Components of Strong Joinery. Jeff holds this discussion with every group of students who attend a class in his shop.
-
This video explains why it’s so important to follow the principles explained in the videos that will follow.
-
Subscribe at www.JointEffort.net/blp (link in bio) if you’d like to be notified as each new video becomes available.

@jefflefkowitz says…
“In general, with a live edge board, you have the straightest grain parallel to the bark edge.”
-
Straight Grain is the first of Jeff’s “6 Components of Strong Joinery”. 
-
This message is brought to you by the Joint Effort’s Berea Ladderback Project.
-
Get access to this series and email alerts for each new video when you subscribe at
www.jointeffort.net/blp/ (link in bio)
-
If you’re already a JE subscriber, but you haven’t opted in to get messages about this project, please follow the link in my bio and put your email in the box. That way you’ll get access to videos and future updates about the project.

I have recently been enjoying the work of @chairman.kim
-
He’s a former web developer, based in Singapore who focuses on making chairs. His work has a modern feel to it, but incorporates a lot of woven surfaces.
-
If this appeals to you, I recommend you check him out.
Knocking out one last workbench before I close the shop for the holidays.

ALMOST!!!
-
Caught it about an inch before it was too late. That would have been EXPENSIVE.
-
Always check your fence extension when you got from angled cuts back to sqaure cuts!
-
This is really a warning for future me. You would never make this mistake. By writing it down I’m hoping I’ll remember a little better next time.

What do you do when you forget to put your rungs back in the kiln and they become less than "Super Dry"?
-
This week, @Jefflefkowitz shared a Chairmaker's Story about this with the subscribers of the Joint Effort "Newsletter". During a class with Brian Boggs in 2008, all the students rungs were mistakenly left out of the kiln over night. To save assembly day, Brian showed his students how to they could use their cars and a little sunlight to make a Kentucky Solar Kiln.
-
To see the full video, follow the link in my bio
or
Go to: www.jointeffort.net/blp

While you're there, consider signing of for the FREE Joint Effort "Newsletter" and you'll get a new video each week.

It's more of a note than a letter.
I send it out once a week.
And there's a link to a free video inside.

Chair teacher @jefflefkowitz retired last year after many years of teaching the Berea Ladder Back chair. As Jeff winds down he has invested the time in equipping new teachers to teach that chair design more broadly. One of those new teachers is @markbuildsit. Quickly Adjust Your Boggs Spokeshave

The Boggs Spokeshave, made and sold by Lie-Nielsen, is one of those hand tools that might be intimidating to learn. But once you get the hang of it, you'll wonder how you ever made anything curvy without it.
-
Brian's design is easy to learn and easy to use. You can quickly remove the blade for sharpening. After that's done, set-up and adjustment take less than 60 seconds.

Any part that has tenons goes through three-phase process.
-
Step 1 - First we get rid of as much extra material as we can without turning the part down to it’s final dimensions. This helps the next step go faster.
-
Step 2 - The parts go into the light bulb kiln until they are “Bone Dry”. Usually a week. This ensures that the final tenon can’t possibly shrink and loosen in it’s mortise after we assemble the chair.
-
Step 3 - Turn the tenons and, in this case, the rest of the part down to it’s final size and shape. We put everything back in the kiln to keep dry until it’s time for assembly.
-
You’ll learn all these steps, and much more, when you make a chair during one of my in-person and remote chair making classes. Message me if you’d like to learn more.
-

Made some new doohickeys last night.
-
With my remote Berea Ladderback class in full swing, I’m constantly searching for ways to make it easier to build these chairs by yourself.
-
In a regular class there are always an extra pair of hands to help out. At home, not so much.
-
One of those steps that’s truly awkward without help is measuring the openings for the slats. You have to adjust the length of a jig as you try to hold each end at just the right height and angle.
-
These little doohickies give to a positive stop to rest the ends of the jig on.
